[There is confusion in the script, with the farmer 1st described as selling "beef," then "cattle." Logically, he was selling cow carcasses. And the implication is that this farmer's dead cows were in some way related to the recent cattle die-off in Malimpung, already suspected to be from anthrax. If any of our readers in Indonesia can sort this out for us, it would be appreciated.

Indonesia has not reported any anthrax outbreaks in 2015 and 2014, which, considering the frequency of this livestock disease in that country, more likely reflects an official report absence more than a disease absence.

To find Sulawesi, go to http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/indonesia_adm_2002.jpg. To find Malimpung in Sulawesi Selatan, go to: http://www.fallingrain.com/world/ID/38/Malimpung.html. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4083988,184.]
